article.headline: Georgia 99, Fla Atlantic 84
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Rashad Wright scored a career-high 25 points, hitting five shots from outside the 3-point line, and Georgia pulled away in the second half for a 99-84 victory over Florida Atlantic on Tuesday night. The Bulldogs (2-0) remained unbeaten under new coach Dennis Felton, albeit against weak competition. They opened with a victory over Western Carolina, then defeated a team that went 7-21 last season. Florida Atlantic (0-2) pulled within 64-60 on Wes Edwards' dunk with 11 minutes remaining, but Georgia put the game away with 22-6 run. Wright made back-to-back 3s, and Damien Wilkins finished the spurt with a steal and two-handed dunk. Wright didn't have any troubles with cramps, which forced him to miss most of the second half against Western Carolina. The senior point guard eclipsed his previous career high of 17 points against LSU last season. Wilkins scored 24 points for Georgia, which shot 53 percent from the field to overcome 20 turnovers. The Bulldogs also had another big night at the free-throw line, hitting 30-of-36. Wilkins was 8-of-10 at the line, Jonas Hayes and Levi Stukes were both perfect in six attempts, and Wright made 6-of-7. All five starters scored in double figures. In the opener, Georgia made 32 free throws -- the fourth-highest total in school history -- to hold off the Catamounts. Three players did most of the scoring for Florida Atlantic. Earnest Crumbley and Mike Bell had 23 points apiece, while Pierre Tucker added 21. But Georgia consistently beat the Owls' trapping, pressing defense, leading to plenty of easy shots and clear looks at the basket. Tucker carried Florida Atlantic in the first half, scoring 17 points, but he was limited by foul trouble in the final period. Georgia led 46-40 at the break. The Bulldogs got all but five points from their starters, which figures to be a trend for a team rebuilding after the scandal that ousted coach Jim Harrick. Georgia dressed only seven players on scholarship. Hayes had a career-best 20 points and 11 rebounds, while Steve Daniels also had a double-double with 12 rebounds and 10 points. Stukes scored 15 points, but the freshman also had five turnovers in just 22 minutes.
